# AI Hub - rebuild the .exe at the end of every task

The user wants a single `dist\AIHub.exe` that they can double-click on a
clean Windows machine. The `build_exe.bat` in the repo root takes care
of everything (auto-installs Python via winget if missing, creates a
`.venv\`, installs `requirements.txt` + `pyinstaller`, then runs
`pyinstaller --onefile --windowed`). The PySide6 / Qt 6 runtime ships
inside the bundle - no Flutter SDK, no Qt SDK, no Visual Studio C++
workload required.

**At the end of a Cursor task you MUST:**

1. Make sure every new pip dependency Cursor introduced is written into
   [requirements.txt](../../requirements.txt). `build_exe.bat` reads
   that file - if a dependency is missing there, the produced .exe
   will crash at runtime even though dev mode worked.
2. Make sure every new data file that needs to be inside the .exe
   (icons, fonts, prompt JSONs, …) is wired into `build_exe.bat` via
   the `pyinstaller ... --add-data "<src>;<dst>"` flag (Windows uses
   `;` as the separator; macOS / Linux use `:`). Code-only changes do
   not need this.
3. Run `build_exe.bat` via the Shell tool as the **last** step of the
   task. The script is idempotent and a no-op when `dist\AIHub.exe`
   is newer than every `.py` under `main.py` and `src\` (use
   `build_exe.bat --force` if a forced rebuild is genuinely needed).
4. If `pyinstaller` fails, fix the cause (missing data file, missing
   pip dep, broken import, …) and rerun. The task is **not** done
   until `build_exe.bat` exits with code 0 and `dist\AIHub.exe`
   exists.

## Hard rules - never break these

- Do **not** delete `build_exe.bat` or any of its self-bootstrap steps
  ("works on a clean Windows machine" is the entire point).
- Do **not** swap `pyinstaller` for `flet pack` / `flet build windows`
  - the project no longer depends on Flet, and the latter needs the
  Flutter SDK + Visual Studio C++ workload, which violates the
  "no prerequisites" promise.
- Do **not** commit `build\`, `dist\`, `.venv\`, or `*.spec` (they are
  in `.gitignore`).
- Do **not** hard-code an absolute path inside `build_exe.bat`. The
  script must run from the repo root via `pushd "%~dp0"`.
- Do **not** delete the repo-local `hooks\` folder. It contains
  PyInstaller hooks (`hook-src.sections.py`,
  `hook-src.services.py`) that explicitly enumerate every auto-
  discovered submodule. Without them, `pyinstaller`'s
  `--collect-submodules src.sections` silently drops project-local
  packages when paired with `--collect-all qtawesome`, and the
  frozen .exe boots with ZERO sections (the debug log shows
  ``discover_done | count=0 keys=[]``).

## When NOT to rebuild

Skip the final `build_exe.bat` only when **all** of these are true:

- The change is documentation-only (`.md` files, comments) AND
- No `.py` file under `main.py` or `src\` was touched AND
- `requirements.txt` was not touched.

In every other case, rebuild.

## How to add a runtime asset to the .exe

1. Drop the file under `assets\` (or another folder that is **not**
   `src\`).
2. Open `build_exe.bat` and append the asset to the `pyinstaller` line:

   ```bat
   pyinstaller --noconfirm --onefile --windowed --name AIHub ^
       --add-data "assets\my_data;assets\my_data" ^
       --hidden-import pyperclip ^
       --collect-submodules PySide6 ^
       %ICON_ARG% ^
       main.py
   ```
3. Re-run the script. The asset is now embedded in the produced exe.

## How the bundled icon system works

Icons are rendered via [QtAwesome](https://github.com/spyder-ide/qtawesome)
(see `src/qt/icons.py`). QtAwesome bundles the **Material Design Icons
6** font (and a handful of others) inside its own wheel and lazy-loads
them through Qt's font database the first time `qta.icon(...)` is
called. `build_exe.bat` already pulls every font + char-map into the
.exe via `--collect-all qtawesome` and `--collect-submodules qtpy`, so
you do not need to touch the build script when adding a new icon. To
make a new icon available in the app:

1. Pick a glyph from <https://pictogrammers.com/library/mdi/>.
2. Add a constant to `src/qt/icons.py`:
   `MY_NEW_ICON = "mdi6.<kebab-case-name>"`.
3. Use it the usual way: `IconLabel(Icons.MY_NEW_ICON, color=..., size=...)`.

Do **not** hand-write a `"mdi6.X"` string at a call site - everything
must go through an `Icons.X` constant so the registry stays the single
source of truth.

## How the repo-local PyInstaller hooks work

`build_exe.bat` passes `--additional-hooks-dir hooks` to PyInstaller so
the analyser picks up the `.py` files in `hooks\`. Two hooks live
there today:

- `hooks\hook-src.sections.py` - walks `src\sections\` at build time
  and adds every `.py` file inside each section folder as a hidden
  import. This is what makes the runtime auto-discovery (see
  `src\sections\__init__.py`) work inside the frozen .exe. Adding a
  new section folder needs **no** edit to the hook: the next
  `build_exe.bat` run picks it up automatically.
- `hooks\hook-src.services.py` - same idea for the shared service
  layer (`src\services\*.py`). A few services (`html_pdf`,
  `ai_provider`) import their backends lazily, so we list every
  public service module explicitly.

If you add a new auto-discovered package under `src\<key>\`, mirror
this pattern: drop a `hooks\hook-src.<key>.py` next to the existing
ones, walk the folder with `pathlib.Path`, and append each `.py` file
to `hiddenimports`. Do **not** invent a different mechanism.
